Some of the many, specific safety features to prevent a chemical accident include:



- Computer-controlled safety systems on our chemical reaction vessels to ensure that any deviations from the intended operating conditions are immediately identified and corrected;



- Safety procedures that reduce the potential for human error which could lead to a storage tank overfill;



- Secondary containment dikes around storage tanks to contain a spill;



- Spill containment around unloading stations to mitigate the impact of a leak;



- Acrylonitrile barge unloading operations are continuously attended by operators who have received specialized training in US Department of Transportation (DOT) requirements;



- Extensive safety information about the processes available to employees;



- Written operating procedures that include emergency response actions;



- Comprehensive employee and contractor training programs to promote consistently safe work practices;



- Maintenance programs to ensure ongoing equipment reliability - includes equipment testing and inspection;



- Safety procedure to review proposed plant modifications before they are implemented for possible hazards (this is called "Management of Change");



- Safety pre-qualification for all contractors;



- Safety reviews prior to startup of our processes; and,



- Safety permitting procedures that control hazards during special operations such as welding (Hot Work) and other maintenance activities



0.5 FIVE YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY



The Bay St. Louis site has an outstanding record of accident prevention, which demonstrates its commitment to public and worker safety. Even minor incidents are investigated to identify what went wrong and to learn how to prevent future occurrences.



